Newcastle coal futures broke another record high at $400 per tonne and are now up more than 100% since the beginning of 2022  as mounting sanctions on Russia for invading Ukraine led to an international energy crunch and exacerbated concerns over the commodities supply. Germany is poised to create coal reserves for electricity power plant operators  while Italy announced it could reopen some shuttered coal plants. Asian customers have also been scrambling to find alternative supplies to replace Russian coal. Aside from Ukraine headlines  investors were already bullish on coal since early 2022 amid supply disruptions in top exporting countries such as Indonesia and Australia.
